Here, the social and religious landscape encourages those exposed to violence to see past events as impermanent and illusory, where debriefing, working-through, or processing past events only solidifies suffering and may even cause illness. Resilience in Dharamsala is understood as sems pa chen po, a vast and spacious mind that does not fixate on individual problems, but rather uses suffering as an opportunity to generate compassion for others in the endless cycle of samsara. A big mind view helps to see suffering in life as ordinary. And yet, an intriguing paradox occurs. As Lewis deftly demonstrates, Tibetans in exile have learned that human rights campaigns are predicated on the creation and circulation of the trauma narrative; in this way, Tibetan activists utilize foreign trauma discourse, not for psychological healing, but as a political device and act of agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBuddhismzIndiazDharmsāla. 0aCultural psychiatryzIndiazDharmsāla. 0aPsychic traumazIndiazDharmsāla. 0aResilience (Personality trait)zIndiazDharmsāla. 0aSufferingxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aTibetan diaspora. 0aTibetansxMental healthzIndiazDharmsāla. 0aTibetanszIndiazDharmsālaxReligion. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aResilience, Trauma, Buddhism, Dharamsala, Tibetan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTi